The paper deals with the computational complexity of a problem related to triangulations of points in the plane, which is a classic topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The proof involves reductions from the NP-complete problems of 3-SAT and Subset Sum, which are well-known problems in complexity theory and combinatorics (cs.DS, cs.CC). The paper also uses techniques from discrete mathematics, such as graph theory and combinatorial optimization, to analyze the problem and its properties (cs.DM). Finally, the paper has implications for approximation algorithms, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that studies the design and analysis of algorithms that find near-optimal solutions to hard problems (cs.CC).
